Reference-contexts: In addition to these simple pixel-based methods, several authors have suggested to use the spatial relationships between the image pixels to locate agricultural fields for subsequent classification on a field basis <ref> (e.g. Janssen 1994, Schoenmakers 1995) </ref>. Although this use of domain knowledge offers some improvement over pixel-based classification, it remains unsuited to handle mixed pixels. The data-driven decomposition method we propose combines the advantages of the decomposition approach and field-based classification. <p> Since we know that our scenes are a collection of agricultural fields, we can discriminate between pure and mixed pixels by locating the pure pixel clusters. These clusters can sometimes be found with the help of ancillary information sources such as topographical maps <ref> (Janssen 1994) </ref>, but it is also possible to segment the image using standard image processing techniques. <p> Once the pure pixels belonging to a cluster have been identified, they can be classified either on an individual basis or by some field-based approach that is more accurate <ref> (Janssen 1994) </ref>. Most remaining pixels are 4 probably mixed and should be decomposed rather than classified. Thus, the accuracy of an crop area estimate can be increased by making a segmentation of the image in order to classify the pure pixels and decompose the mixed pixels.
